# Branch Policy

This rule defines how work reaches `main`: **always through a branch and a pull request**, including documentation, rules, skills, and CI config. **Direct pushes to `main` are not allowed** for normal work; GitHub **branch rulesets** should enforce this ([BRANCH_PROTECTION.md](docs/technical/BRANCH_PROTECTION.md)).

## Branch requirements (all change types)

Use a **named branch** for every deliverable commit, then open a **PR** to `main`:

| Change type | Branch examples |
|-------------|-----------------|
| Feature | `feature/FEAT-XXX-short-description`, `feature/NNN-short-description` |
| Task | `task/TASK-XXX-short-description`
| Bug / hotfix | `bug/BUG-XXX-‚Ä¶`, `hotfix/HOTFIX-XXX-‚Ä¶`
| Chore / docs / rules / skills | `chore/NNN-short-description`, `docs/short-description` |

**Includes:** application code, tests, `docs/`, `.cursor/rules/`, `.cursor/skills/`, `.claude/skills/`, `pyproject.toml`, Docker, GitHub Actions, project markdown ‚Äî anything that becomes a commit.

## Why documentation and rules use branches too

- Keeps **history reviewable** (PR diff, discussion, linked issues).
- Matches **branch protection** (no accidental `git push origin main`).
- Aligns with [.claude/skills/merge-via-pr/SKILL.md](mdc:.claude/skills/merge-via-pr/SKILL.md).

## Issues and GitHub

- **Never** implement a GitHub issue **only** on `main` ‚Äî always use a branch (`feature/‚Ä¶`, `task/‚Ä¶`, `chore/‚Ä¶`) and merge via PR ([ISSUE_IMPLEMENTATION_WORKFLOW.md](docs/portfolio/ISSUE_IMPLEMENTATION_WORKFLOW.md)).
- When work is **verified complete**, update **issue checkboxes** (body) and use **`Closes #NNN`** in the PR description so the issue closes on merge.

## Exceptions (rare)

- **Repository administrators** may use GitHub **bypass** for emergencies only (not routine workflow).
- **Bots** (Dependabot, etc.) may merge via rules configured on the repo.

## Enforcement

### AI agent behaviour

1. **Before committing:** if current branch is `main`, **create a branch** (`git checkout -b chore/‚Ä¶` or `feature/‚Ä¶`) then commit.
2. **Never suggest** `git push origin main` for hand-written commits.
3. **Follow** [merge-via-pr skill](mdc:.cursor/skills/merge-via-pr/SKILL.md).

### Pre-commit / pre-push hooks

Hooks still run tests and lint; they do **not** enforce ‚Äúnot on main‚Äù ‚Äî **branch protection** on GitHub does.

## Branching strategy: choosing the base

### When on `main`

1. **Pull** `git pull origin main`.
2. **Create branch** `git checkout -b <type>/<name>`.
3. **Implement** and **push** the branch; open **PR** to `main`.

### When work depends on another open branch

1. Branch from that branch or rebase onto it after it merges.
2. See [api-v1-delivery-sequence.md](docs/portfolio/api-v1-delivery-sequence.md) for stacked **API v1** PRs.

### Examples

| Scenario | Action |
|----------|--------|
| Normal issue work | Branch from `main` ‚Üí PR ‚Üí merge |
| Depends on unmerged branch | Branch from that branch or stack PRs |
| Small doc-only fix | Still use a branch + PR (e.g. `docs/fix-typo-api`) |

